04408nam a22006255i 9780691237633DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211989nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912376337 a10.1515/97806912376332doi  a(DE-B1597)602097  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aB3998 7aPHI0090002bisacsh04a199/.4922231 aYovel, Yirmiyahu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpinoza and Other Heretics, Volume 1 :bThe Marrano of Reason /cYirmiyahu Yovel. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1989  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Sources -- tCHAPTER 1. Prologue: Heretic and Banned -- tCHAPTER 2. Spinoza, the Marrano of Reason -- tCHAPTER 3 . The Split Mind: New Jews in Amsterdam -- tCHAPTER 4. Marranos in Mask and a World without Transcendence: Rojas and La Celestina -- tCHAPTER 5. Spinoza, the Multitude, and Dual Language -- tCHAPTER 6. Knowledge as Alternative Salvation -- tCHAPTER 7. Epilogue Spinoza and His People: The First Secular Jew? -- tAfterword to Volume I -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis ambitious study presents Baruch Spinoza (1632-1677) as the most outstanding and influential thinker of modernity—and examines the question of whether he was the "first secular Jew." A number-one bestseller in Israel, Spinoza and Other Heretics is made up of two volumes—The Marrano of Reason and The Adventures of Immanence. Yirmiyahu Yovel shows how Spinoza grounded a philosophical revolution in a radically new principle—the philosophy of immanence, or the idea that this world is all there is—and how he thereby anticipated secularization, the Enlightenment, the disintegration of ghetto life, and the rise of natural science and the liberal-democratic state.The Marrano of Reason finds the origins of the idea of immanence in the culture of Spinoza's Marrano ancestors, Jews in Spain and Portugal who had been forcibly converted to Christianity. Yovel uses their fascinating story to show how the crypto-Jewish life they maintained in the face of the Inquisition mixed Judaism and Christianity in ways that undermined both religions and led to rational skepticism and secularism. He identifies Marrano patterns that recur in Spinoza in a secularized context: a "this-worldly" disposition, a split religious identity, an opposition between inner and outer life, a quest for salvation outside official doctrines, and a gift for dual language and equivocation. This same background explains the drama of the young Spinoza's excommunication from the Jewish community in his native Amsterdam. Convention portrays the Amsterdam Jews as narrow-minded and fanatical, but in Yovel's vivid account they emerge as highly civilized former Marranos with cosmopolitan leanings, struggling to renew their Jewish identity and to build a "new Jerusalem" in the Netherlands.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aImmanence (Philosophy)xHistoryy17th century. 0aMarranos. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069123763340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691237633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691237633/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK